{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508590"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:07:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:07:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2810"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2810"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.05,0.74,0.14,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2788"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102422"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2788","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2788"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2810"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84896"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3745"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3786"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35594"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42571"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43213"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44356"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102422"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with confusion, fever and a productive cough for the past four days. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 118/min, blood pressure 110/75mmHg, respiratory rate 33/min, temperature 40\u00b0C, and SpO2 89% on room air. Chest auscultation reveals crackles and decreased breath sounds in the right lower chest. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis laboratory results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin  132 g/L (135- 180)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWCC                  14 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0 \u2013 11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium             138 mmol/L (137 \u2013 145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium        4.5 mmol/L (3.5 \u2013 4.9)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea                   10 mmol/L (2.7 \u2013 8.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray shows right lower lobe infiltrates. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In addition to admission to hospital and oxygen therapy, which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV Vancomycin","Oral Augmentin","IV Ceftriaxone and Azithromycin","IV Piperacillin-Tazobactam","Non-invasive ventilation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with fever, productive cough, chest crackles, decreased breath sounds, and chest X-ray showing lobar infiltrates most likely has a diagnosis of community-acquired pneumonia (CAP).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of pneumonia is based on its severity. The severity of pneumonia can be calculated by the CURB-65 score. CURB-65scoring is summarized in table 1.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a CURB-65 score of 4 (ie, confusion, urea \u003E7 mmol/L, respirations \u226530/min, age \u226565 years). Hence, he should be treated along the protocol for high-severity CAP. The management for severe CAP is urgent admission to hospital and empirical \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E (recommended using \u003Cstrong\u003EIV Ceftriaxone plus Azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV Vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used for suspected or confirmed methicillin-resistant \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E (MRSA) infections. In community-acquired pneumonia, MRSA is an uncommon pathogen unless there are specific risk factors such as recent hospitalization, prior MRSA infection, or residence in a long-term care facility. This patient has no such risk factors mentioned, making vancomycin an inappropriate first-line choice for empiric therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAugmentin\u003C/strong\u003E is a combination antibiotic, combining amoxicillin (a beta- lactam) with clavulanic acid (a beta- lactamase inhibitor). An oral dose of a broad spectrum antibiotics is appropriate for low-moderate severity CAP, however, is inappropriate for severe CAP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf there is suspicion of \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas\u003C/em\u003E infection, or if this patient had comorbidities including bronchiectasis, COPD, or chronic glucocorticoid use, then \u003Cstrong\u003EIV piperacillin- tazobactam\u003C/strong\u003E could be indicated. This patient does not have any of these comorbidities and the microbiologic cause of the lobar pneumonia has not been discovered, therefore IV piperacillin- tazobactam is unlikely to be the best current management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECAP is not usually an indication for \u003Cstrong\u003Enon-invasive ventilation.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The CURB-65 scoring system should be used to determine the severity of community-acquired pneumonia (CAP).","Severe community-acquired pneumonia (CAP) should be immediately treated with empirical IV antibiotics (such as Ceftriaxone plus Azithromycin) and hospital admission.","Patients with fever, productive cough, chest crackles, decreased breath sounds, and chest X-ray showing lobar infiltrates most likely have a diagnosis of community-acquired pneumonia (CAP)."],"references":["Williams JM, Greenslade JH, Chu KH, Brown AF, Lipman J. Utility of community-acquired pneumonia severity scores in guiding disposition from the emergency department: Intensive care or short-stay unit? Emerg Med Australas. 2018;30(4):538-546. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29609223/","Sparham S, Charles PG. Controversies in diagnosis and management of community-acquired pneumonia. Med J Aust. 2017;206(7):316-319. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28403766/","Lim WS, Baudouin SV, George RC, Hill AT, Jamieson C, et al. Pneumonia Guidelines Committee of the BTS Standards of Care Committee. BTS guidelines for the management of community acquired pneumonia in adults: update 2009. Thorax. 2009;64(3):iii1-55. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19783532/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84896"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2810"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"11766"},{"type":"media","id":"11767"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"11766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/11766"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/614f998b-ef85-4530-b7ca-0c950a0827c0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/614f998b-ef85-4530-b7ca-0c950a0827c0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"